&lt;/blockquote&gt;</content><author><name>Tao He</name></author><category term="Jekyll" /><summary type="html">The jekyll-gitbook theme can be used just as other Jekyll themes and support remote theme on Github Pages, see the official guide as well.</summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Why Jekyll with GitBook</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/jekyll-gitbook/jekyll/2019-04-27-why.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Why Jekyll with GitBook" /><published>2019-04-27T00:00:00+03:00</published><updated>2019-04-27T00:00:00+03:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/jekyll-gitbook/jekyll/why</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/jekyll-gitbook/jekyll/2019-04-27-why.html">&lt;p&gt;GitBook is an amazing frontend style to present and organize contents (such as book chapters
and blogs) on Web. The typical to deploy GitBook at &lt;a href=&quot;https://pages.github.com&quot;&gt;Github Pages&lt;/a&gt;
is building HTML files locally and then push to Github repository, usually to the &lt;code class=&quot;language-plaintext highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;gh-pages&lt;/code&gt;
branch. However, it’s quite annoying to repeat such workload and make it hard for people do
version control via git for when there are generated HTML files to be staged in and out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This theme takes style definition out of generated GitBook site and provided the template
for Jekyll to rendering markdown documents to HTML, thus the whole site can be deployed
to &lt;a href=&quot;https://pages.github.com&quot;&gt;Github Pages&lt;/a&gt; without generating and uploading HTML bundle every time when there are
